      {
        question: "An NP is teaching NP students about cell death mechanisms. Which statement accurately distinguishes apoptosis from necrosis at the cellular level?",
        options: ["Apoptosis involves cell swelling and membrane rupture; necrosis involves cell shrinkage and membrane-bound body formation","Apoptosis activates caspases and exposes phosphatidylserine for phagocytic clearance without inflammation; necrosis releases DAMPs through membrane rupture triggering inflammatory cascades","Both apoptosis and necrosis require ATP and activate the same caspase cascade but differ only in the triggering stimulus","Necrosis is always pathological while apoptosis never occurs in normal physiological processes"],
        correct: 1,
        rationale: "Apoptosis is characterized by cell shrinkage, chromatin condensation, caspase activation, DNA fragmentation into nucleosomal ladders, phosphatidylserine externalization (eat-me signal), and formation of apoptotic bodies that are phagocytosed without inflammation. Necrosis involves cell swelling (oncosis), organelle swelling, membrane rupture, and release of DAMPs (HMGB1, ATP, uric acid) that activate innate immune responses through pattern recognition receptors, causing inflammation. Apoptosis requires ATP (energy-dependent); necrosis results from ATP depletion. Apoptosis is essential in normal physiology (embryogenesis, immune cell selection, tissue turnover)."
      }
